Project: Twitter US Airline Sentiment¶

Background and Context:¶

Twitter possesses 330 million monthly active users, which allows businesses to reach a broad population and connect with customers without intermediaries. On the other hand, theres so much information that its difficult for brands to quickly detect negative social mentions that could harm their business.

That's why sentiment analysis/classification, which involves monitoring emotions in conversations on social media platforms, has become a key strategy in social media marketing.

Listening to how customers feel about the product/service on Twitter allows companies to understand their audience, keep on top of whats being said about their brand and their competitors, and discover new trends in the industry.

Data Description:¶

A sentiment analysis job about the problems of each major U.S. airline. Twitter data was scraped from February of 2015 and contributors were asked to first classify positive, negative, and neutral tweets, followed by categorizing negative reasons (such as "late flight" or "rude service").

Dataset:¶

The dataset has the following columns:

  • tweet_id
  • airline_sentiment
  • airline_sentiment_confidence
  • negativereason
  • negativereason_confidence
  • airline
  • airline_sentiment_gold
  • name
  • negativereason_gold
  • retweet_count
  • text
  • tweet_coord
  • tweet_created
  • tweet_location
  • user_timezone

# Instead of creating my own utility functions, I am reusing some functions
# that were used in various MLS sessions.

# I have enhanced the function that was used in class to be able to display a
# single feature or two features.
# In the case of two features, the second feature is rendered through the hue.
# I have also enhanced the function to sort the results by the height of the
# column instead of by the name of the column.

# function to create labeled barplots

def labeled_barplot(data, feature, feature2=None, perc=False, n=None):
    """
    Barplot with percentage at the top

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column that primarily drives x axis
    feature2: dataframe column that drives the hue of the related items of the major x-axis feature
    perc: whether to display percentages instead of count (default is False)
    n: displays the top n category levels (default is None, i.e., display all levels)
    """

    total = len(data[feature])  # length of the column
    count = data[feature].nunique()

    count2 = 1;
    if ( feature2 is not None ):
      count2 = data[feature2].nunique()

    if n is None:
        n = count
        plt.figure(figsize=(count2*(count + 1), 10))
    else:
        plt.figure(figsize=(count2*(n + 1), 10))

    plt.xticks(rotation=90, fontsize=15)
    if ( feature2 is None ):
      # Plot the single feature, sorting the columns based on the height
      # of the main feature (value_count())
      ax = sns.countplot(
          data=data,
          x=feature,
          order=data[feature].value_counts().index[:n],
      )
    else:
      # Plot with the second feature as a hue, sorting the columns based
      # on the height of the main feature (value_count())
      ax = sns.countplot(
          data=data,
          x=feature,
          hue=feature2,
          order=data[feature].value_counts().index[:n],
      )

    for p in ax.patches:
        if perc == True:
            label = "{:.1f}%".format(
                100 * p.get_height() / total
            )  # percentage of each class of the category
        else:
            label = p.get_height()  # count of each level of the category

        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2  # width of the plot
        y = p.get_height()  # height of the plot

        ax.annotate(
            label,
            (x, y),
            ha="center",
            va="center",
            size=12,
            xytext=(0, 5),
            textcoords="offset points",
        )  # annotate the percentage

    plt.show()  # show the plot

# Look at the sentiment of the tweets by specific airlines.

Observation: The data shows that some airlines have received a lot more negative tweets than others. Let me frame these numbers as a percentage of the total tweets that a specific airline gets. This will give me an idea of how each airline is faring in terms of customer sentiments.

  • United --> Negative = 69%; Positive = 13%
  • US Airways --> Negative = 78%; Positive = 9%
  • American --> Negative = 71%; Positive = 12%
  • Southwest --> Negative = 49%; Positive = 24%
  • Delta --> Negative = 43%; Positive = 24%
  • Virgin America --> Negative = 36%; Positive = 30%

Given this distribution, it appears that although tweets related to Virgin America are the fewest, it gets the largest percentage of positive tweets of all the airlines.

US Airways gets the smallest percentage of positive tweets, at 9%, while 78% of the tweets about US Airways is negative. This airline is really doing poorly in customer sentiment.

  1. Remove HTML tags
  2. Remove special characters and punctuation
  3. Remove all the numbers from the text
  4. Tokenize the words
  5. Remove stopwords
  6. Convert to lowercase

# Now I need to remove the set of non-ASCII characters, if any from the set of tokenized words.
# I am reusing a method that was used in the MLS session to do this, instead of creating my own version.
def remove_non_ascii(words):
    """Remove non-ASCII characters from list of tokenized words"""
    new_words = []
    for word in words:
        new_word = unicodedata.normalize('NFKD', word).encode('ascii', 'ignore').decode('utf-8', 'ignore')
        new_words.append(new_word)
    return new_words

tweets['text'] = tweets['text'].apply(lambda words: remove_non_ascii(words))

# Inspect to make sure that the text has all been tokenized. Display 15 records, not 5.

# Next convert all characters to lowercase.
# I am reusing a method that was used in the MLS session to do this, instead of creating my own version.
def to_lowercase(words):
    """Convert all characters to lowercase from list of tokenized words"""
    new_words = []
    for word in words:
        new_word = word.lower()
        new_words.append(new_word)
    return new_words

tweets['text'] = tweets['text'].apply(lambda words: to_lowercase(words))

# Inspect to make sure that the text has all been tokenized. Display 15 records, not 5.
tweets.head(15)

# Now remove all punctuation from the words.
# I am reusing a method that was used in the MLS session to do this, instead of creating my own version.
def remove_punctuation(words):
    """Remove punctuation from list of tokenized words"""
    new_words = []
    for word in words:
        new_word = re.sub(r'[^\w\s]', '', word)
        if new_word != '':
            new_words.append(new_word)
    return new_words

tweets['text'] = tweets['text'].apply(lambda words: remove_punctuation(words))

# Time to remove the stopwords from the text.

# We have previously downloaded a standard set of stopwords from the nltk library.
# However, in free-flowing text, as in Twitter comments, we do need to retain certain
# stopwords, else we will get incorrect sentiment analysis. Especially important is the
# 'not' word, without which we may interpret the reverse sentiment.

en_stopwords = stopwords.words('english')

# Note that my custom list doesn't include words like "shouldn't" or "doesn't", etc. That is
# because we have already removed contractions from our tokenized text, hence we are not
# likely to encounter contractions. We don't need to remove such contracted words from the stopwords.
customlist = ['not', 'ma']

# I will customize the stopwords list for my analysis here
en_stopwords = list(set(en_stopwords) - set(customlist))

# Remove all words that are part of the customized English stopwords list we built just now.
# I am reusing a method that was used in the MLS session to do this, instead of creating my own version.
def remove_stopwords(words):
    """Remove stop words from list of tokenized words"""
    new_words = []
    for word in words:
        if word not in en_stopwords:
            new_words.append(word)
    return new_words


tweets['text'] = tweets['text'].apply(lambda words: remove_stopwords(words))

# Inspect to make sure that all stopwords have been removed from the tokenized words. Display 15 records, not 5.
tweets.head(15)

import wordcloud

# To display the word cloud, I am going to adapt and reuse a function that was used in the MLS class.
def show_wordcloud_text(features_text, title):
    stopwords = set(wordcloud.STOPWORDS)                                  # instantiate the stopwords from wordcloud
    
    fig_wordcloud = wordcloud.WordCloud(stopwords=stopwords,background_color='white',          # Setting the different parameter of stopwords
                    colormap='viridis', width=800, height=600).generate(features_text)
    
    plt.figure(figsize=(14,11), frameon=True)                             
    plt.imshow(fig_wordcloud)  
    plt.axis('off')
    plt.title(title, fontsize=30)
    plt.show()

# To display the word cloud, I am going to adapt and reuse a function that was used in the MLS class.
def show_wordcloud(data, feature, title):
    text = ' '.join(data[feature].astype(str).tolist())                   # Converting all column data for the feature into a list
    show_wordcloud_text(text, title)

# Define a function to convert text sentiment to number
def get_score(sentiment):
  if sentiment == 'negative':
    return 1
  if sentiment == 'neutral':
    return 2
  return 3

Define a set of utility functions to make it easy to do some repeatable activities¶

In [446]:
# Define a reusable function to make it easy to plot the errors for the various models
# It also returns the number of estimators that lead to optimal learning (min error)

def find_optimal_learner(cross_val_scores):
  # plotting the error as k increases
  base_ln = [x for x in range(1, 25)]
  error = [1 - score for score in cross_val_scores]                  #error corresponds to each nu of estimator
  optimal_learners = base_ln[error.index(min(error))]                #Selection of optimal nu of n_estimator corresponds to minimum error.
  plt.plot(base_ln, error)                                           #Plot between each nu of estimator and misclassification error
  xy = (optimal_learners, min(error))
  plt.annotate('(%s, %s)' % xy, xy = xy, textcoords='data')
  plt.xlabel("Number of base learners")
  plt.ylabel("Misclassification Error")
  plt.show()
  return optimal_learners
In [447]:
# Define a utility function to display the confusion matrix

def display_confusion_matrix(y_test, result):
  # Finally, time to plot the results as a confusion matrix
  conf_mat = confusion_matrix(y_test, result)

  print(conf_mat)

  print(metrics.f1_score(y_test, result,average='micro'))

  display_results = ['negative', 'neutral', 'positive']
  df_cm = pd.DataFrame(conf_mat, index = display_results, columns = display_results)

  plt.figure(figsize = (10,7))
  sns.heatmap(df_cm, annot=True, fmt='g')

Word Cloud of top 40 important features from the CountVectorizer + Random Forest based model¶

In [464]:
# Create a utility function to be able to extract the most important features
def extract_imp_features(vec, clf):
  all_features = vec.get_feature_names()              #Instantiate the feature from the vectorizer
  top_features=''                                         # Addition of top 40 feature into top_feature after training the model
  feat=clf.feature_importances_
  features=np.argsort(feat)[::-1]
  for i in features[0:40]:
      top_features+=all_features[i]
      top_features+=' '
  return top_features

Summary¶

  • I have successfully cleaned and pre-processed tweets to be able to extract features and create classifiers.
  • The majority of tweets have negative sentiments for the airlines, with the worst airlines being US Airways and the best airlines being Virgin America.
  • The biggest complaints are about customer service, followed by late flight, cancelled flight, and lost luggage.
  • The two vectorizers, CuntVenctorizer and TfidfVectorizer, both did a good ob of extracting the most important features. The TfidfVectorizer did a better job in extracting the negative sentiments more prominently, which is a better reflection of the general sentiment of the tweets.
  • The classification models gave us fairly accurate results, with CountVectorizer+random forest giving 75% accuracy, and TfidfVectorizer+random forest giving us 76% accuracy.
  • Both rounds of classification were done carefully with validation done through k-fold cross-validation on training data set, thus avoiding data leakage into the test data.
  • Both models started off with an initial radom forest tree and were then optimized to get the optimal learner. The optimal learner was then used to train the model and test against the test data.
  • I limited the max feature set to 2000 for the model analysis. I can possibly increase the number of features (with additional compute and time cost) to see if the effectiveness of the classifier model can be improved.
  • I was not able to determine why 'JetBlue' showed up so prominently as a feature, and I need to look at all the tweets to see why it shows up so prominently.
